{"cursor":"8189","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = Department of Energy and Climate\nChange |type = Department |logo = Energy Climate Change logo.svg |logo_width =\n200px |logo_caption = |seal = |seal_width = |seal_caption = |formed = 2008\n|date1 = |date1_name = |date2 = |date2_name = |preceding1 = |preceding2 =\n|dissolved = |superseding = |jurisdiction = United Kingdom |headquarters = |latd\n= |latm = |lats = |latNS = |longd = |longm = |longs = |longEW = |region_code =\nGB |employees = |budget = Â£1.5 billion (current) & Â£1.5 billion (capital) in 2011-\n12  |chief1_name = Edward Davey MP |chief1_position = Secretary of\nState for Energy and Climate Change |chief2_name = |chief2_position =\n|parent_agency = |child1_agency = |child2_agency = |website = |footnotes = }}\n\nThe 'Department of Energy and Climate Change' ('DECC') is a British government\ndepartment created on 3 October 2008 by Prime Minister Gordon Brown to take over\nsome of the functions of the Department for Business, Enterprise and Regulatory\nReform (energy) and Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (climate\nchange). It is led by the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change,\ncurrently the Rt Hon Ed Davey MP.\n\nThe Department released a major White Paper in July 2009 setting out its purpose\nand plans. See [http://www.decc.gov.uk/en/content/cms/publications/lc_trans-\n_plan/lc_trans_plan.aspx The UK Low Carbon Transition Plan], The Stationary\nOffice, 2009-07-15. Retrieved on August 4, 2009. The majority of DECC's\nspending is on managing the UK's historic nuclear sites, in 2012/13 this being\n69% of its budget spent through the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority, and this\nis expected to increase when the last of the UK's Magnox reactors are shut down\nand no longer produce an income.\n","linknr":524,"url":"Department_for_Energy_and_Climate_Change","recorded":1375067216,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Department_of_E